  "articleSummary": "Thearticle argues that “just adding more engineers” never speeds up a late software project because the coordination cost grows quadratically with team size (n · (n‑1)/2), quickly outweighing any extra capacity. It cites classic research—from Brooks’s *Mythical Man‑Month* to modern studies in *Accelerate* and IEEE—showing that larger teams incur heavy communication overhead, long onboarding delays (3‑6 months for senior engineers), and more merge‑conflict and incident risk, while small, autonomous teams consistently deliver faster and with higher quality. Real‑world examples such as Microsoft’s DevDiv findings, Amazon’s two‑pizza rule, and the *Team Topologies* optimal team size reinforce the thesis. The tone is a data‑driven analysis mixed with a cautionary rant, using the “communication paths” metaphor and the O(n²) formula as recurring framing devices. It targets engineering managers, tech leads, and senior executives who grapple with deadline pressure and staffing decisions.",
